# OrangeHRM – Cucumber BDD Test Automation Framework

End-to-end **BDD** automation framework for the public **OrangeHRM** demo, built with
Cucumber + Selenium + TestNG, with **Allure** reporting and a **Jenkins** pipeline.

> **Application under test:** https://opensource-demo.orangehrmlive.com/
> **Demo credentials** (published openly by OrangeHRM for their sandbox): `Admin` / `admin123`

---

## Tech stack

| Layer            | Choice                                                        |
|------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------|
| Language         | Java 17                                                       |
| BDD              | Cucumber 7.18.1 (`cucumber-java`, `cucumber-testng`)          |
| Browser driver   | Selenium 4.21.0 — **built-in Selenium Manager** (no WebDriverManager) |
| Runner           | TestNG 7.10.2 via `@CucumberOptions` + parallel `@DataProvider` |
| Reporting        | Allure 2.27.0 (`allure-cucumber7-jvm`) + AspectJ 1.9.22 weaver |
| Build            | Maven (surefire 3.2.5, allure-maven 2.12.0)                  |
| CI               | Jenkins declarative pipeline (`Jenkinsfile`)                 |

---

## Project layout

```
orangehrm-cucumber-framework/
├── pom.xml
├── testng.xml
├── Jenkinsfile
├── src
│   ├── main/java/com/orangehrm
│   │   ├── config/ConfigReader.java        # config.properties + -D overrides
│   │   ├── driver/DriverFactory.java       # chrome/firefox/edge via Selenium Manager
│   │   ├── driver/DriverManager.java       # ThreadLocal<WebDriver> (parallel-safe)
│   │   ├── pages/                          # Page Objects (oxd- locators)
│   │   └── utils/                          # WaitUtils, ScreenshotUtils
│   └── test
│       ├── java/com/orangehrm
│       │   ├── hooks/Hooks.java            # driver lifecycle + failure screenshots
│       │   ├── runners/TestRunner.java     # @CucumberOptions glue
│       │   └── stepdefinitions/            # step glue (one class per module)
│       └── resources
│           ├── features/                   # 8 .feature files, 40 scenarios
│           ├── config/config.properties
│           └── allure.properties
```

---

## Prerequisites

- **JDK 17+** (`java -version`)
- **Maven 3.8+** (`mvn -version`)
- A real **browser** installed (Chrome/Firefox/Edge). Selenium Manager auto-resolves the matching driver — no manual download.
- **Allure CLI** (optional, for `allure serve`): https://allurereport.org/docs/install/
- Internet access to the OrangeHRM demo site.

---

## Running the tests

From the project root:

```bash
mvn clean test
```

### Useful overrides (any `config.properties` value works as `-D`)

```bash
# Headless run on Firefox
mvn clean test -Dbrowser=firefox -Dheadless=true

# Run scenarios in parallel (3 threads)
mvn clean test -Ddataproviderthreadcount=3

# Different browser + headless + parallel together
mvn clean test -Dbrowser=chrome -Dheadless=true -Ddataproviderthreadcount=3
```

### Tag filtering (Cucumber)

```bash
# Only the login feature
mvn clean test -Dcucumber.filter.tags="@login"

# Everything EXCEPT write operations (recommended on the shared public demo)
mvn clean test -Dcucumber.filter.tags="not @write"

# Smoke subset
mvn clean test -Dcucumber.filter.tags="@smoke"
```

> **About `@write` scenarios:** A few scenarios (add employee, add candidate, etc.) create
> records on the **shared** public demo. They are tagged `@write` so you can exclude them with
> `-Dcucumber.filter.tags="not @write"` if the demo data has drifted or another user is mid-test.

---

## Allure report

```bash
# Option A — Maven plugin (serves on a local port)
mvn allure:serve

# Option B — Allure CLI against the raw results
allure serve target/allure-results

# Option C — generate a static site
allure generate target/allure-results --clean -o target/allure-report
```

Failure screenshots are auto-attached to the Allure report by the `@After` hook.

---

## What's covered (40 scenarios across 8 features)

| Feature              | Scenarios | Highlights                                                        |
|----------------------|-----------|-------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `login.feature`      | 8         | valid login, 3× invalid (outline), empty username/password, forgot-password, logout |
| `navigation.feature` | 12        | every main-menu module routes to the correct URL (outline)        |
| `dashboard.feature`  | 3         | widgets present, quick-launch shortcuts, user account menu        |
| `admin.feature`      | 4         | search user, role-filter options, filter by role, reset           |
| `pim.feature`        | 4         | employee list, search, reset, **@write** add employee             |
| `leave.feature`      | 3         | Apply Leave page, leave-type options, My Leave list               |
| `recruitment.feature`| 3         | candidates list, **@write** filter by status, **@write** add candidate |
| `directory.feature`  | 3         | directory cards, filter by job title, reset                       |

---

## Jenkins

The included `Jenkinsfile` is a declarative pipeline with build parameters:

- `BROWSER` (chrome/firefox/edge), `HEADLESS` (true/false), `TAGS` (Cucumber filter), `THREADS`
- Runs `mvn clean test` with those parameters
- Publishes the Allure report and archives `target/allure-results` + `target/cucumber-reports`

> **Before first run**, make sure the `tools { jdk … maven … }` names in the `Jenkinsfile`
> match the tool installation names configured under *Manage Jenkins → Tools*, and that the
> **Allure** Jenkins plugin is installed.

---

## Notes on locators

Page objects target OrangeHRM's Angular-style `oxd-` classes and label-driven inputs
(e.g. typing into a field by its visible label, selecting from `oxd-` dropdowns, waiting for
the loader spinner to disappear). Result assertions are deliberately **count-agnostic**
(they check for the presence of a results summary rather than a hard-coded row count) so they
stay green even as the shared demo's data changes.
